snippet.textDisplay:
This is amazing. It's great to see influential people speak up about things like this; the copious amount of misinformation and stigmatization around ASD is astounding, and it warms my heart to see people that are genuinely interested in learning about it. I was diagnosed with Tourettes, a condition on the spectrum, at 9.

We're so often discarded and thought of as people who can't do anything, but we're just as capable as anyone else is about anything. The worst part is that most of the mistreatment isn't intentional. It's based on misinformation and ignorance.
Thank you for this. It's really appreciated.

snippet.textDisplay: I am also on the spectrum, I have Asperger’s syndrome and ADHD, I’m grateful for my mom because she’s the reason I’ve become good at socializing; I still have trouble with it time to time. Not many people know I have autism cuz I’m higher functioning. But for me I focused on art and music, and maintaining eye contact use to be really hard but now I test myself how long I can keep eye contact. I also like that girl have anxiety disorder, towards junior and senior year it got worse it not only was just panicked attacks but I started getting painful stomach aches due to anxiety and stress. My school (not my teachers but the people in charge of disability shit) refused to give me an IEP  and went on to say my mom was a liar and  said I didn’t have autism. I had to get an advocate and even with her I wasn’t able to get what I needed. But my teachers were in my side through it all, supporting me, & help pushing me to succeed. And you know what I survived high school and graduated on time because of them. I really am thankful for my mom, friends and teachers.

snippet.textDisplay:
Growing up as someone with a neurological disorder, I was bullied a lot. But I especially remember my first bully was my first grade teacher.
She would read a book called “No, David!” To the class and then look at me and two other kids that were actually causing a disruption in the class when David did something bad.
But I wasn’t even as bad as she was making me out to be, I literally just couldn’t focus and day dreamed a lot. So I can relate to the class room nightmares these people had to face especially when we literally can’t help how our brains work.

snippet.textDisplay:
Hey there! I'm on the autistic spectrum, a bit unsure of what it was but I think it was aspergers? I'm Dutch and don't really know all the English words for it all so yeah. Anyway when I saw this video it really made me happy. I don't know a lot of people with autism, probably like 2 to 3 people.


Luckily I happened to not be treated badly because of it but because of me not getting proper help yet (I probably will finally have the right help soon so yay) because they weren't truly specialised in what I needed I developed more issues. Although the situation with my autism is fine my family situation not so much.. we all suspect (or pretty much know) my dad has autism as well. Hell he knows it too but doesn't accept it.


I barely see him nowadays because he never listens to me when I say I won't come to his place. (It's a complicated situation). Now recently my mom and my dad went to some system therapy, which went horrible of course like jeez my dad literally smoked weed outside in front of the building lmao.


But I overheard from a convo my mom was having on the phone since I sometimes unintentionally eavesdrop that my dad apparently said that "I have multiple children, why would I change just because one is special?". That deeply hurt, it still does of course. If he had some major mental issues I might've took it with a grain of salt but jeez- he's just under the influence of fucking weed all the time. Like I don't understand how ANYONE could think like that. Just.. what the fuck. Why? What have we ever done other than being different in a way? Even if we push the whole mental issue aside. Why say that about your child..?


Anyway I respect you for making this video, I think it's a good way to spread awareness that autistic people aren't all idiots and stuff like that. Even if I'm saying it myself I think I function fine, I don't think anyone would see that I'm autistic unless I write it on my forehead. Anyway idk how to stop this so I'll just say bye.


Bye and have a wonderful day! Wether you read through this or not :) <3

snippet.textDisplay: Thank you so much Anthony. As an autistic person you don't know how much it means for me to see you treat us as equals. I have been treated like a baby, an idiot, or even like I am not human being so much in my lifetime. To see you respect us and try to understand makes me happy. I am glad you gave us a platform to speak, not a lot of people let us speak for ourselves. I would also like people to know not to support Autism Speaks (search autism speaks controversy to see why), and instead support other groups such as the Autistic Self Advocacy Network who help by providing resources and programs for people on the spectrum.

snippet.textDisplay: The video was great and insightful. But I think it is important to mention that the people interviewed here are all high functioning. Autism is a spectrum and people suffering from more severe form of autism often experience a lot of self harm, severe anxiety and more hindering symptoms and are actually suffering a lot.  In that case I think it is still important to do research and find ways to alleviate those symptoms for better quality of life.

snippet.textDisplay: I myself have autism and was very lucky in the fact that I was diagnosed at the age of six. Many people only find out later in life which can make getting help a harder adjustment. Since I was constantly having sensory overloads, it would cause me to be impatient angry and unfiltered and I would hit scream kick cry and have full on hellish tantrums when I didn’t get what I wanted or I felt misunderstood. This is absolutely not the case for everyone but sadly it was for me and my family and myself had to deal with the consequences. I can’t remember what age but sometime around when I was eight I believe, I started going to a therapist with my mother to help improve my behaviour. The lady that was assigned to us was horrid. I don’t mean to say she only did a bad job, she was an awful person to me. She would say that ‘I was ruining my wonderful mother’s life’, that ‘I was abusing her’ which in a way I was but she told me that I was an awful person and didn’t deserve my mother and how after all she did for me I was being an ungrateful demon. Every time we went, which was weekly, I would cry and scream because I didn’t want to return to her and feel like I was a parasite to my loved ones lives. One time even, when we were driving there, I had opened the car door while we were on the road because I dreaded going so much. One of the worst aspects was that she would do this in front of my mother who was crying too. She had broken me down so much and never built me back up. I later years later found out that this lady never even believed I had autism. I am still young and unlike the people in this video find autism to be a grand burden but I am also grateful for the unique outlook and special qualities that come with having autism. For anyone dealing with any mental health issues, know that you are loved by others who can relate and that there are people who though they don’t know exactly what you are going through, can feel the same way you do. 😊💕✍🏻
